The paper deals with self-stabilizing systems, which are most often used in distributed applications, and proposes a protocol for a self-stabilizing two-dimensional quadtree that satisfies monotonic searchability. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with routing and searching for nodes, which suggests that it could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of messages, which suggests that it could belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper deals with systems that recover from illegal states, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with high-dimensional searchability, which suggests that it could belong to the Distributed Systems (cs.Distributed Systems) sub-category.
